Load Data

The first dataset that we are going to look at is named Credit, a simulated data set containing information of a large number of customers. It is in the library ISLR1. Therefore, we will install this library in order to access the dataset. Type install.packages("ISLR") in the R console.

library(ISLR) # Loading the package ISLR.

Data Set Summary

  1. How large is this data set?
dim(Credit) # The dimension (rows by columns) of the data set
  1. What are the columns?
names(Credit)
  1. Which of the variables are categorical? Which ones are numerical? We can take a peek of the data set by viewing its first a few rows (e.g., first 10 rows).
head(Credit, 10) # The head function shows the first a few rows of the data set.

A detailed explanation of the data set can be found by ?Credit or help(Credit) in the console.

Graphs

  1. Create a frequency table for a variable.
table(Credit$Student) # summary(Credit) also works

To convert the frequency table to a relative frequency table, we can divide the numbers in the table by the total number of customers in the data set. If you remember the total number of customers is 400, do table(Credit$Student) / 400. Otherwise, we can use the length function to calculate the total so that we do table(Credit$Student) / length(Credit$Student).

  1. Create a pie chart.
freq <- table(Credit$Student) 
pie(freq, main = "Student Status")
  • The code is equivalent to pie(table(Credit\$Sstudent), col = c("lightblue", "lightcoral")).
  • The arrow sign (<-) in the first line of this code chunk deposits contents in the right-hand side of the arrow to the left-hand side of the arrow. In this case, it puts the student status frequency table in a R variable freq, so that in the future, any time when we need the frequency table, we simply call freq instead of typing table(Credit$Student) over and over again.
  • The option main = "Student Status" adds a title to the graph.
  1. Create a bargraph. We have already assigned freq to be the frequency table in the previous code chunk, so we can continue using it.
barplot(freq, main = "Student Status")
  • How to make the y-axis display relative frequency?
  • How to change the labels from Yes/No to Student/Non-student?

Other ways to display categorical data.

  1. Donut plot. This donut function is not a built-in R function. It is included in the nicer.R file written by your instructor.
source("https://albums.yuanting.lu/sta126/nicer.R")
donut(freq, main = "Student Status")

[Bonus] Graphic Skills +

Below you will learn how to customize graphs.

  • Customized colors.
    • The col = c(“lightblue”, “lightcoral”) option provides two colors to the graph.
    • The c function combines its arguments (e.g., “lightblue”, “lightcoral”) and creates a vector.
  • Customized group tags.
    • The labels option allows us to change the group tags in a pie chart.
    • The names option allows us to change the group tags in a bar graph.
  • Customize text labels on the y-axis.
    • The ylab option allows us to change the text label on the y-axis.
  • Use lines to shade bars and slices.
    • The density option provides the density of line segments to each bar or slice.
    • The angle option sets the angles of the line segments (in degrees).
library(ISLR)
freq <- table(Credit$Student) 
pie(freq, 
    col = c("lightblue", "lightcoral"), 
    labels = c("Non-student", "Student"), 
    main = "Student Status")

barplot(freq, 
        density = c(20, 10), 
        angle = 60, 
        names = c("Non-student", "Student"), 
        ylab = "Frequency", 
        main = "Student Status")
